faithful chronological order, thus inviting readers to witness the ways thematic and formal concerns have evolved from Trecartin's earliest movies to his more recent multimedia cinematic installations. Through precisely chosen screen captures extracted directly from the movies, Zulueta demonstrates the serious attention paid to camera angles, mise-en-scène, and shot transitions, thus revealing and reflecting on the concepts that underwrite and are underwritten in these narratives. Giving careful attention to Trecartin's network of layered references to the grotesque and abject, carnivalesque and ludic, and camp imagery, Zulueta illustrates and explains how the artist takes on reality television, technology, fashion, consumption, and cyberspace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aVideo artzUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art History. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Art. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Queer Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846895240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438468952423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438468952/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles